put. There could be complications with thread handling, especially if attempts to join occur while edits are underway. It's all a bit tricky!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering exception handling and streams**\\n\\nI'm weighing the benefits of using `finally` in a `try` block, especially to ensure that if an edit throws an exception, I can still close resources robustly. There might be concerns about style guidelines against empty catches. It looks like I need to check if I should run the build since the user said it failed, but I can't inspect the compile. I also wonder if writing to `PipedOutputStream` before reading from `PipedInputStream` on the same thread would cause any issues. It's all quite intricate!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Thinking through pipe management**\\n\\nI’m considering what happens if the pipe gets full after a timeout. In that case, blocking in write could lead to issues if I try to close it while writing. It seems closing `PipedInputStream` before the terminal is essential, so I should reverse the close order: close the terminal first, then close `nanoInput` and `nanoWriter`. Also, I’m curious whether repeated `ctrl-x` commands might cause issues since they could queue up if the terminal isn't ready. It’s all a bit complicated!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_7OfqQixN2iPGt6R3VrSxciI3|fc_0b16fe48a743cbe90169f80d96e7e48197b3e702cbbdecb028", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.jline/jline-reader/4.0.0/src/test/java/org_jline/jline_reader/LineReaderImplTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import java.io.ByteArrayOutputStream;\nimport java.io.PipedInputStream;\nimport java.io.PipedOutputStream;\n", "newText": "import java.io.ByteArrayOutputStream;\nimport java.io.IOException;\nimport java.io.PipedInputStream;\nimport java.io.PipedOutputStream;\n"}, {"oldText": "        } catch (Exception ignored) {\n            editorClosed.set(true);\n        }\n", "newText": "        } catch (IOExcepti